Nigerian Breweries Plc has said its revenue for the 2021 financial year rose by 29.7 per cent to N437.19bn from N337.01bn in 2020. A statement by the Company Secretary/Legal Director, Uaboi Agbebaku, said the breakdown of the 2021 audited results showed that the company’s profit grew by 71.8 per cent from N7.53bn in 2020 to N12.93bn in 2021. Agbebaku said the board of directors commended the management for placing the company on the path to recovery from the debilitating impact of the COVID-19 pandemic and other challenges faced during the year. “The board would be recommending to shareholders at the forthcoming annual general meeting the declaration of a total dividend of N12.92bn at 50 kobo per share representing a 100 per cent dividend payout ratio,” he said. The statement noted that the company had earlier in October 2021 paid an interim dividend of N3.23bn, which translated to 40 kobo per share. It said the final proposed dividend of N9.69bn at N1.20 per share would be payable to shareholders upon approval on April 25, 2022. According to the statement, only qualifying shareholders whose names appear on the company’s register of members at the close of business on March 9, 2022 would be paid the final dividend. Agbebaku said the company remained committed to delivering improved performance in the years ahead. He said it would also continue to deploy cost-efficient measures to keep its balance sheet strong and healthy while ensuring that the safety and welfare of its employees, customers, and partners remain well protected. Nigerian Breweries Plc has declared a revenue of N337.01 billion for the financial year ended December 31, 2020. The revenue represented an increase of 4.3 per cent compared with N323 billion recorded in the corresponding period of 2019. The company disclosed this in its audited financial statement to newsmen signed… In "Business" By Chinyere Joel-Nwokeoma Lagos - The Nigerian Breweries Plc on Monday attributed 41 per cent drop posted in profi